Movie.title: Jason Bourne
Movie.summary: The most dangerous former operative of the CIA is drawn out of hiding to uncover hidden truths about his past.

item.text: Much of Jason Bourne consists of grim action set pieces interspersed with long sequences of people sitting in front of computer screens. Somehow the movie is simultaneously frenetic and static, going nowhere really, really fast.
item.author: Dmitry Samarov

item.text: Of all the indignities Damon's title character, dug out of retirement after nine years, has to suffer in the disappointing Jason Bourne, the worst is how out-of-touch the new conspiracy he unravels feels
item.author: Alison Willmore

item.text: The movie feels like the work of a capable but uninspired cover band. Before we had Treadstone; now we have re-Treadstone.
item.author: Christopher Orr

item.text: Greengrass is as dexterous as ever, yet the result, though abounding in thrills, seems oddly stifled by self-consciousness and, dare one say, superfluous.
item.author: Anthony Lane

item.text: Damon owns the role and the movie. It's a tense, twisty mindbender anchored by something no computer can generate: soul.
item.author: Peter Travers

item.text: Sure, Jason Bourne has all the hallmarks of a story - there are characters who are involved in scenes, and those scenes indicate the forward march of time - but nothing here actually matters.
item.author: Barry Hertz

item.text: Greengrass stages three breathless marquee action sequences, including a smash-em-up car chase down the Las Vegas Strip that would make even the "Fast and Furious" gang stop and gawk.
item.author: Adam Graham

item.text: The experience of Jason Bourne may ironically work best for those who are able to put past chapters out of their mind and just thrill to the movement on the screen.
item.author: Peter Howell

item.text: The biggest disappointment, among many, for Greengrass's reboot of the franchise he and Damon had abandoned for a decade is how divorced Bourne is from his original species.
item.author: Will Leitch

item.text: Director Paul Greengrass refuses to tangle with any of the true-life topics he's borrowing for gravitas
item.author: Amy Nicholson

item.text: This new installment in the series is one of the better ones.
item.author: Peter Rainer

item.text: Despite regurgitating elements from the founding trilogy, Jason Bourne represents the best the series has yet offered.
item.author: James Berardinelli

item.text: Even when Jason Bourne doesn't click with the same rhythm as its predecessors, it has a weight that outclasses nearly every other big action movie around.
item.author: Jake Coyle

item.text: Director Paul Greengrass tries to up the perambulatory drama with lots of cuts, swishes, jiggles, and wobbles from his camera and swellings from his soundtrack, but the energy just isn't there.
item.author: Matthew Lickona

item.text: Made with a palpable sense of urgency, this tense, propulsive motion picture is a model of what mainstream entertainment can be like when everything goes right.
item.author: Kenneth Turan

item.text: An idea-starved vestigial tail on the Bourne trilogy that wrapped up nicely nine years ago.
item.author: Chris Klimek

item.text: Jones's dyspeptic deadpan is the only fun thing in Jason Bourne.
item.author: David Edelstein

item.text: Bourne used to be an anguished amnesiac. Now he remembers who he is, but this fourth episode of the franchise forgot to make him human.
item.author: Joe Morgenstern

item.text: A ho-hum entry in the previously electrifying franchise.
item.author: Rafer Guzman

item.text: It reunites director Greengrass and once-and-future (and still buff) Matt Damon for a Jason Bourne movie so familiar-in-a-good-way that they dispensed with a Ludlum-esque title descriptor and simply called it Jason Bourne.
item.author: Jim Slotek

similar.item: 13 Hours: The Secret Soldiers of Benghazi
